Region
------
5 Apr 2015 West Africa: The Ebola orphans taking desperate measures to survive
http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/ebola/11515372/The-Ebola-orphans-taking-desperate-measures-to-survive.html
[Street Child charity reports many of the thousands of children stricken by the virus have turned to crime and prostitution simply to care for their siblings. Orphans are also at increased risk of physical and sexual abuse and teenage pregnancies. The study also found cases of Ebola orphans raped, becoming pregnant or turning to prostitution. Others are agreeing to marry while still very young simply so they can to find an alternative family.]

7 Apr 2015 West Africa: Western media overlooks Africa role in fighting Ebola disease http://sputniknews.com/africa/20150407/1020578262.html#ixzz3WeJba6io
[According to an African Union (AU) spokesperson, Africa's effort to tackle the Ebola virus has been disregarded by Western media, even though Africans are the front line in fighting the deadly disease.]

7 Apr 2015 West Africa: Health workers on Ebola frontlines serve countries, risk own lives
http://www.worldbank.org/en/news/feature/2015/04/06/healt-workers-on-ebola-frontlines-serve-countries-risk-own-lives
[Before the surge of foreign health-care workers in Liberia, Sierra Leone and Guinea, African health workers rushed to serve in health-care facilities, many of which did not provide training for the job, nor did they have barrier-protection equipment. Many of the African workers paid with their lives. According to a certified midwife and nurse, the hospital where she worked was a "warfront." Speaking of her co-workers, she said, "They started to die, one by one."]

8 Apr 2015 West Africa: Ebola cases in West Africa drop to lowest figure in a year
http://www.jpost.com/Breaking-News/WHO-30-new-Ebola-cases-lowest-weekly-figure-in-nearly-a-year-396605
[According to the World Health Organization, in the past week, 30 confirmed cases were reported in West Africa, the smallest number since May 2014. Guinea had 21 new infections; unsafe burials of bodies continued in Guinea and unknown chains of transmission could be a source of new infections in the coming weeks]
[See WHO update [2] above for summary of cases. - Mod.LK]

Non-governmental organizations
------------------------------
6 Apr 2015: World warned: Prepare for more Ebola-like outbreaks
http://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/world-warned-prepare-for-more-ebolalike-outbreaks-10157494.html
[According to Dr David Nabarro, the United Nations Secretary-General, outbreaks of deadly zoonotic diseases, such as Ebola, could become more likely due to climate change and human encroachment into untouched natural habitats.]

6 Apr 2015: All lives matter -- Why do Sierra Leonean and American clinicians with Ebola get different care?
http://www.slate.com/articles/health_and_science/medical_examiner/2015/04/ebola_treatment_in_sierra_leone_and_united_states_who_decides_where_doctors.html
[This article was written by a nurse working with Partners in Health. She brings up very difficult ethical issues being confronted in this outbreak where West Africans and Americans (and Europeans, etc.) are working side by side selflessly towards the same goal, to help with patient care. The distinction between their geographic origin becomes problematic only when they become ill, and different standards of care are applied. There is no easy answer, other than to bring the standard of care in West Africa up to the level in the developed world, and that is difficult. - Mod.LK]

7 Apr 2015: Ebola and health care workers -- look back in anger: special report in the May 2015 issue of Hospital Employee Health
http://www.ahcmedia.com/blogs/2-hicprevent/post/135233-ebola-and-health-care-workers-look-back-in-anger
[After the 1st occupational infections of Ebola in US history, legal, and ethical questions remain]

Vaccines, Drugs
---------------
7 Apr 2015: Ebola vaccine 2015 -- Guinea seen as best hope for preventative drug trials, but time is running out
http://www.ibtimes.com/ebola-vaccine-2015-guinea-seen-best-hope-preventative-drug-trials-time-running-out-1872220
["You cannot test a vaccine for Ebola if there's no Ebola. You need an active epidemic, which is why there has been such a global collaborative effort to start these trials as quickly as possible." Dr Charlie Weller of the Wellcome Trust in the UK.]

8 Apr 2015: Side effects temporarily halted Ebola vaccine safety trial
http://www.latimes.com/science/sciencenow/la-sci-sn-vsv-ebola-vaccine-20150407-story.html
[According to researchers, human safety tests on a promising experimental Ebola vaccine (VSV-ZEBOV) were halted temporarily when 22 per cent of Geneva subjects experienced arthritis or joint pain for a period of about a week a week to several months. Phase 1 trials conducted on 52 volunteers in the United States showed the vaccine to be safe. Participants in the Geneva trials were given a higher dose of the vaccine]

8 Apr 2015: Ebola vaccine by Baltimore's Profectus BioSciences advances to human trials
http://www.bizjournals.com/baltimore/blog/cyberbizblog/2015/04/ebola-vaccine-by-baltimores-profectus-biosciences.html
[The vaccine, VesiculoVax, prevented monkeys from contracting and dying of Ebola Makona, the strain of the virus that led to the current Ebola outbreak in West Africa.
URL to Nature Journal:
http://www.nature.com/nature/journal/vnfv/ncurrent/full/nature14428.html

